title: For Sale:  Japanese type 99 training rifle
postcontent:
Japanese type 99 training rifle. Starting in the 1920's, the Japanese government required all junior and senior high school boys to have two hours a week of military training. Several companies started producing the necessary training rifles for this purpose. Unfortunately most training rifles did not bear markings that identified their origin.
These training rifles had no standard design and were often made from older models of military rifles or parts from these rifles. Therefore you will find many variations of the same model. There are known models that used 1888 Mauser, type 99, type 30, and type 38 rifle parts. These training rifles continued to be produced until the late 1930's. Some of these rifles could not be fired while others would fire wooden bullet blank ammunition. Many of the blank firing rifles were made with smooth bore barrels. Rarely would any of these rifles fire the standard service round. Nearly all of these training rifles could carry bayonets.

title: For Sale:  Sellers need to be responsive.
location: Franklinton, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Several buyers are expressing frustration with sellers who post and never respond. I've had the same experience. I've responded within the first hour of the posting and never received a response. Sellers need to be courteous, and at least inform buyers if the they have another potential buyer. 

Another problem is posting with no intention of selling. Such behavior negatively impact and devalue this site

My final concern is the need for responsible transactions. Must posting indicate buyer / seller must produce valid ID, CCW permit and agree to sign a fire-arm-bill of sale. This is an excellent and responsible practice. I'm a advent buyer from this site and a few times I've travel over 100 miles to complete the financial transaction, only to find out that the seller will not sign a fire-arm bill of sale. For me this is a deal breaker and a waste of time. Let's keep the government out of our business, but we must remain diligent and responsible by agreeing to all terms of sell as posted. Signing a fire-arm bill of sale, protects everyone. If don't, we are only inviting government intervention.

This is a great site, let's keep it that way.
